ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.
M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: The person who initiates sexual activity is responsible for getting consent for the other person.
Consent must be given for each step in a sexual encounter.
If someone initiates sex, but during foreplay says they no longer want to, they have not given consent.
If someone doesn't verbally say no to sex, they have given consent.
If someone doesn't physically resist sex, they have given consent.
Consent for oral sex is consent for vaginal sex.
If someone undresses or allows a man to undress her, she is giving consent for sex.
Consent for sex one time in consent for future sex.
If you and your sexual partner are both drunk, you don't have to worry about consent.
Regardless of the circumstances, if someone has sex with another person, they have given consent.
Mixed signals can sometimes mean consent.
Telling someone that you love them to get sex is no big deal.
Someone who goes into someone else's bedroom is giving consent for sex.
If you are in a steady relationship, you still have to get consent.
